f antiretroviral protease inhibitors. This positive turn of events led to a decline in patient populations and, ultimately, to the closure of Unit 371. Czerwiec’s restrained, inviting drawing style and carefully considered narrative examine individual, institutional, and community responses to the AIDS epidemic—as well as the role that art can play in the grieving process.Deeply personal yet made up of many voices, this history of daily life in a unique AIDS care unit is an open, honest look at suffering, grief, and hope among a community of medical professionals and patients at the heart of the epidemic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAIDS (Disease)xNursingvComic books, strips, etc. 0aHIV infectionsxNursingvComic books, strips, etc. 0aMedicinevComic books, strips, etc. 7aCOMICS & GRAPHIC NOVELS / Nonfiction / Biography & Memoir.2bisacsh  aAIDS.  aChicago.  aHIV.  aIllinois Masonic Medical Center.  aart.  adeath.  aepidemic.  agraphic novel.  agraphic.  ahospital.  alife.  amedicine.  aoral history.  apatient.  award.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107452380 cprintz978027107818240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271079677?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271079677423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271079677/original  a978-3-11-074523-8  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles